Name: Japan Consumer Price Index Inflation Rate
Periodicity:
Annual From Dec 1868 To Dec 1921
Monthly From Jan 1922 To Jan 2019
Metadata:
Sources: Williamson (1868-1900); League of Nations (1922-1945); Bureau of Statistics, Monthly Statistics of Japan (1946-)
Notes: WilliamsonÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s cost of living index was constructed from prices in Tokyo for rice, soybeans, and salt (LTES vol. 8: 153-154), and prices of firewood and salted fish (LTES vol. 8: 138-151). The missing years 1894-95 for the price of salt were filled by linear interpolation. The (fixed) weights were derived from consumption budgets for the Ã¢â‚¬Å“typicalÃ¢â‚¬Â family (LTES vol. 8: 138-141 and vol. 6: 136-137). The weights were: cost of living = (rice).70 + (soy).07 + (salt).01 + (firewood).08 + (salted fish).14.Data are annual for 1900 through 1921 and monthly thereafter.
The CPI is calculated as the weighted arithmetic mean with fixed base (Laspeyres formula, 2000 = 100), covers the whole of Japan, excludes ""one-person households"". (The CPI which covers the all households including one-person households is also calculated as a supplementary index.)
The index covers 598 items. The prices of index items are collected in the monthly Retail Price Survey in principle. In this survey, prices are collected in 167 sample cities, towns and villages, selected by using probability sampling method to represent the whole country. The prices are surveyed once a month in principle, but the prices of fresh food and cut flowers are collected three times a month as their prices sharply fluctuate day by day. Approximately 230,000 price quotes are obtained each month from 30,000 establishments and 22,000 rental units. The weights are based on the 2000 Family Income and Expenditure Survey and are revised once every five years. The base year is also changed every five years. Seasonally adjusted indices are also calculated.
